Definition 4.3. If $\,\mathbb{M}\,$ is an $\,\mathcal{R}$-module, let us write $\,\mathbb{M}_{sch}\,$ for the module scheme defined as: $\mathbb{M}_{sch}:=((\mathbb{M}^{*})_{qc})^{*}.$
Definition 3.4. An $\,\mathcal{R}$-module $\,\mathbb{M}\,$ is called a module scheme if there exists an $\,R^{0}$-module $\,N\,$ such that $\,\mathbb{M}\simeq\mathcal{N}^{*}$.
Definition 3.17 For $\mathfrak{g}$ as above, we denote by $\mathcal{C}_{\mathfrak{g}}$ the smallest full, exact Grothendieck subcategory of $\mathfrak{g}\text{-mod}$ containing $\widetilde{\mathrm{Tens}}_{\mathfrak{g}}$. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 4.41 Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a semi-artinian Grothendieck category such that the class of isomorphism classes of simple objects is a set. We denote by $E\mathcal{C}$ the Ext-algebra of $\mathcal{C}$, by definition equal to $\bigoplus\operatorname{\mathrm{Ext}}^{p}(T^{\prime},T),$ made into an algebra via the Yoneda product; the summation ranges over the isomorphism classes of simple objects $T$, $T^{\prime}$, and integers $p\geq 0$. Note that $E\mathcal{C}$ is graded by placing $\operatorname{\mathrm{Ext}}^{p}$-groups in degree $p$. The category $\mathcal{C}$ is said to be Koszul if $E\mathcal{C}$ is generated in degree one. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 2.1 An object $X$ in a Grothendieck category if semi-artinian if every nonzero quotient of $X$ has nonzero socle. A Grothendieck category is semi-artinian if it has a set of semi-artinian generators. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 5.55 An $\mathcal{A}$-module is locally unitary if it is unitary over some $\mathcal{A}^{r}\subset\mathcal{A}$. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 2.11 For an object $U\in\mathcal{C}$ its corona $\operatorname{\mathrm{cor}}U$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is $\widetilde{U}/U$. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 2.4 If the $X_{i}$ in Definition 2.2 are of finite length (or, equivalently, if $X_{i}$ satisfy Definition 2.1 in [us]), we say that $\mathcal{C}$ is a finite ordered Grothendieck category. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 5.58 For $d\geq 0$, the degree-$d$ homogeneous component $\mathcal{A}^{r}_{d}$ is the direct sum of all spaces of morphisms $\mathrm{T}^{\leq r}\to Y\to Z\to\mathrm{T}^{\leq r},$ where • $Y$ and $Z$ are indecomposable direct summands of $\mathrm{T}^{\leq r}$ such that $\operatorname{\mathrm{soc}}Z\in\mathcal{S}_{i}$ and $\operatorname{\mathrm{soc}}Y\in\mathcal{S}_{j}$; • $d(i,j)=d$ (the defect from Definition 2.7); • the outer arrows are the surjection and inclusion realizing respectively $Y$ and $Z$ as direct summands. The gradings of the various algebras $\mathcal{A}^{r}$ are then compatible with the inclusions $\mathcal{A}^{r}\subset\mathcal{A}^{r+1}$, so $\mathcal{A}$ itself acquires an $\mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0}$-grading. We write $\deg(x)$ for the degree of an element $x\in\mathcal{A}$. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 2.14 Let $X$ be an object of a Grothendieck category $\mathcal{C}$. (1) $X$ is noetherian if it satisfies the ascending chain condition on subobjects; (2) $\mathcal{C}$ is locally noetherian if it has a set of noetherian generators. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 4.32 Suppose the class $\mathrm{Indec}(\mathcal{C})$ of isomorphism classes of indecomposable objects of an abelian category $\mathcal{C}$ is a set. The blocks of $\mathcal{C}$ are the classes of the finest equivalence relation on $\mathrm{Indec}(\mathcal{C})$ requiring that objects $Z,Y$ with $\operatorname{\mathrm{Hom}}_{\mathcal{C}}(Z,Y)\neq 0$ belong to the same class. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 2.2 The above structure makes $\mathcal{C}$ an ordered Grothendieck category provided the following conditions hold: (i) every object in $\mathcal{C}$ is isomorphic to a subquotient of a direct sum $\bigoplus\limits_{i\in I^{\prime}\subset I}X_{i}^{\oplus\gamma_{i}}$ for some subset $I^{\prime}\subset I$ and some cardinal numbers $\gamma_{i}$; (ii) the sets $\mathcal{S}_{i}$ are disjoint, and they exhaust the isomorphism classes of simple objects of $\mathcal{C}$; (iii) simple subquotients of $X_{i}$ which are not subobjects of $\operatorname{\mathrm{soc}}X_{i}$ belong to $\mathcal{S}_{j}$ for $j\prec i$; (iv) each $X_{i}$ decomposes as a direct sum of subobjects with simple socle; (v) for all $i{{\succ}}j$ the maximal subobject $Y_{i{{\succ}}j}\subseteq X_{i}$ whose simple constituents are in various $\mathcal{S}_{k}$ for $i{{\succeq}}k{{\succ}}j$, is the joint kernel of a family of morphisms $X_{i}\to X_{j}$. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 4.20 $\mathbb{T}_{\alpha}$ is the smallest full monoidal subcategory (with respect to $\otimes$) of ${\mathfrak{g}\text{-mod}}$ which contains $V$ and $V^{*}$, and is closed under taking subquotients. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 2.7 Let $i{\preceq}j$ be two elements in a poset $(I,{\preceq})$. The defect $d(i,j)$ is the supremum in $\mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0}\cup\{\infty\}$ of the set of nonnegative integers $q$ for which there is a chain $i=i_{0}{\prec i_{1}\prec\cdots\prec}i_{q}=j$ in $I$. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 2.1. [9] A finitely complete category $\mathbb{C}$ is a Mal’tsev category if every reflexive relation $r\colon R\rightarrowtail X\times X$ is an equivalence relation.
Definition 2.2. [9] A difunctional relation in a finitely complete category $\mathbb{C}$ is an internal relation $r=(r_{1},r_{2})\colon R\rightarrowtail X\times Y$ such that, when we consider the following diagram where both squares are pullbacks and $\operatorname{tw}$ the twisting isomorphism, $\xymatrix{S\save*!/dr-1.5pc/dr:(-1,1)@^{|-}\restore\ar[rr]\ar@{}[d]|(.3){}="A"% \ar@{>->}"A";[d]&&R\ar@{}[d]|(.3){}="B"\ar@{>->}"B";[d]^{-}{r}&T\save*!/ur+1.5% pc/ur:(1,1)@_{|-}\restore\ar[l]\ar@{}[d]|(.3){}="C"\ar@{>->}"C";[d]\\ R\times R\ar[r]_{-}{r_{2}\times r_{1}}&Y\times X\ar[r]_{-}{\operatorname{tw}}&% X\times Y&R\times R\ar[l]^{-}{r_{1}\times r_{2}}}$ the canonical monomorphism $S\cap T\rightarrowtail T$ is an isomorphism.
Definition 1. A restriction category is a category $\mathscr{C}$ equipped with a combinator mapping each morphism $A\xrightarrow{f}B$ to a morphism $A\xrightarrow{\overline{f}}A$ satisfying (i) $f\overline{f}=f$, (ii) $\overline{g}\overline{f}=\overline{f}\overline{g}$, (iii) $\overline{f\overline{g}}=\overline{f}\overline{g}$, and (iv) $\overline{g}f=f\overline{gf}$ for all suitable $g$.
Definition 4. A restriction category $\mathscr{C}$ has compatible (disjoint) joins if it has a restriction zero, and satisfies that for each compatible (disjoint) subset $S$ of any hom set $\mathscr{C}(A,B)$, there exists a morphism $\bigvee_{s\in S}s$ such that (i) $s\leq\bigvee_{s\in S}s$ for all $s\in S$, and $s\leq t$ for all $s\in S$ implies $\bigvee_{s\in S}s\leq t$; (ii) $\overline{\bigvee_{s\in S}s}=\bigvee_{s\in S}\overline{s}$; (iii) $f\left(\bigvee_{s\in S}s\right)=\bigvee_{s\in S}(fs)$ for all $f:B\to X$; and (iv) $\left(\bigvee_{s\in S}s\right)g=\bigvee_{s\in S}(sg)$ for all $g:Y\to A$.
Definition 11. Recall the interpretation of predicates in $\mathcal{L}$ as decisions in $\mathscr{C}$: (i) $\left\llbracket\mathit{tt}\right\rrbracket=\amalg_{1}$, (ii) $\left\llbracket\mathit{ff}\right\rrbracket=\amalg_{2}$, (iii) $\left\llbracket\mathbf{not}~{}p\right\rrbracket=\gamma\left\llbracket p\right\rrbracket$, (iv) $\left\llbracket p~{}\mathbf{and}~{}q\right\rrbracket=\left(\amalg_{1}\overline% {\amalg_{1}^{\dagger}\left\llbracket p\right\rrbracket}~{}\overline{\amalg_{1}% ^{\dagger}\left\llbracket q\right\rrbracket}\right)\vee\left(\amalg_{2}\left(% \overline{\amalg_{2}^{\dagger}\left\llbracket p\right\rrbracket}\vee\overline{% \amalg_{2}^{\dagger}\left\llbracket q\right\rrbracket}\right)\right)\overline{% \left\llbracket p\right\rrbracket}~{}\overline{\left\llbracket q\right\rrbracket}$.
Definition 7. A restriction category is said to be extensive (as a restriction category) if it has restriction coproducts and a restriction zero, and for each map $A\xrightarrow{f}B+C$ there is a unique decision $A\xrightarrow{\langle f\rangle}A+A$ satisfying (D.1): $\nabla\langle f\rangle=\overline{f}$ and (D.2): $(f+f)\langle f\rangle=(\kappa_{1}+\kappa_{2})f$.
Definition 13. Say that programs $p_{1}$ and $p_{2}$ are observationally equivalent, denoted $p_{1}\approx p_{2}$, if for all states $\sigma$, $\sigma\vdash p_{1}\downarrow\sigma^{\prime}$ if and only if $\sigma\vdash p_{2}\downarrow\sigma^{\prime}$.
Definition 2. An inverse category is a restriction category where each morphism is a partial isomorphism.
Definition 9. An inverse category with a disjointness tensor is said to be extensive when each map $A\xrightarrow{f}B\oplus C$ has a unique decision $A\xrightarrow{\langle f\rangle}A\oplus A$ satisfying (D’.1): $(\amalg_{1}^{\dagger}\langle f\rangle)\vee(\amalg_{2}^{\dagger}\langle f% \rangle)=\overline{f}$ (D’.2): $(f\oplus f)\langle f\rangle=(\amalg_{1}\oplus\amalg_{2})f$.
Definition 6. An inverse category $\mathscr{C}$ has compatible (disjoint) joins if it has a restriction zero and satisfies that for all compatible (disjoint) subsets $S$ of all hom sets $\mathscr{C}(A,B)$, there exists a morphism $\vee_{s\in S}s$ satisfying (i) – (iv) of Definition 4.
Definition 14. Say that a model of a structured reversible flowchart language is $I$-well pointed if, for all parallel morphisms $f,g:A\to B$, $f=g$ precisely when $fp=gp$ for all $p:I\to A$.
Definition 10. A model of a structured reversible flowchart language $\mathcal{L}$ consists of a join inverse category $\mathscr{C}$ with a disjointness tensor, further equipped with distinguished objects $I$ and $\Sigma$ satisfying (i) the identity and zero maps on $I$ are distinct, i.e., $\text{id}_{I}\neq 0_{I,I}$, (ii) if $I\xrightarrow{e}I$ is a restriction idempotent then $e=\text{id}_{I}$ or $e=0_{I,I}$, and (iii) each $\mathcal{L}$-state $\sigma$ is interpreted as a total morphism $I\xrightarrow{\left\llbracket\sigma\right\rrbracket}\Sigma$.
Definition 3. In a restriction category, say that parallel maps $f$ and $g$ are disjoint iff $f\overline{g}=0$; and compatible iff $f\overline{g}=g\overline{f}$.
Definition 8. A disjointness tensor on a restriction category is a symmetric monoidal restriction functor $-\oplus-$ satisfying that its unit is the restriction zero, and that the canonical maps $\amalg_{1}=A\xrightarrow{\rho^{-1}}A\oplus 0\xrightarrow{\text{id}\oplus\text{% 0}}A\oplus B\qquad\qquad\amalg_{2}=B\xrightarrow{\lambda^{-1}}0\oplus B% \xrightarrow{\text{0}\oplus\text{id}}A\oplus B$ are jointly epic, where $\rho$ respectively $\lambda$ is the left respectively right unitor of the monoidal functor $-\oplus-$.
Definition 15. Say that a model $\mathscr{C}$ of a structured reversible flowchart language $\mathcal{L}$ is bijective on states if there is a bijective correspondence between states of $\mathcal{L}$ and total morphisms $I\to\Sigma$ of $\mathscr{C}$.
Definition 5. In an inverse category, say that parallel maps $f$ and $g$ are disjoint iff $f\overline{g}=0$ and $f^{\dagger}\overline{g^{\dagger}}=0$; and compatible iff $f\overline{g}=g\overline{f}$ and $f^{\dagger}\overline{g^{\dagger}}=g^{\dagger}\overline{f^{\dagger}}$.
Definition 12. Recall the interpretation of commands in $\mathcal{L}$ (and the meta-command $\underline{\mathit{loop}}$) as morphisms $\Sigma\to\Sigma$ in $\mathscr{C}$: (i) $\left\llbracket\mathbf{skip}\right\rrbracket=\text{id}_{\Sigma}$, (ii) $\left\llbracket c_{1}~{}\mathtt{;}~{}c_{2}\right\rrbracket=\left\llbracket c_{% 2}\right\rrbracket\left\llbracket c_{1}\right\rrbracket$, (iii) $\left\llbracket\mathbf{if}~{}p~{}\mathbf{then}~{}c_{1}~{}\mathbf{else}~{}c_{2}% ~{}\mathbf{fi}~{}q\right\rrbracket=\left\llbracket q\right\rrbracket^{\dagger}% (\left\llbracket c_{1}\right\rrbracket\oplus\left\llbracket c_{2}\right% \rrbracket)\left\llbracket p\right\rrbracket$, (iv) $\left\llbracket\mathbf{from}~{}p~{}\mathbf{loop}~{}c~{}\mathbf{until}~{}q% \right\rrbracket=\operatorname{Tr}_{\Sigma,\Sigma}^{\Sigma}(\beta[p,c,q])$, and (v) $\left\llbracket\mathit{\underline{loop}}[p,c,q]\right\rrbracket=\bigvee_{n\in% \omega}\beta[p,c,q]_{21}\beta[p,c,q]_{22}^{n}$ where $\beta[p,c,q]=(\text{id}_{\Sigma}\oplus\left\llbracket c\right\rrbracket)\left% \llbracket q\right\rrbracket\left\llbracket p\right\rrbracket^{\dagger}:\Sigma% \oplus\Sigma\to\Sigma\oplus\Sigma$. Note also that $f_{ij}=\amalg_{j}^{\dagger}f\amalg_{i}$.
Definition 1.13. A comprehension scheme $P$ on $\mathcal{E}$ is said to restrict to a full and replete subcategory $\mathcal{E}^{\prime}$ of $\mathcal{E}$ if the restriction $P_{|\mathcal{E}^{\prime}}$ is a comprehension scheme on $\mathcal{E}^{\prime}$.
Definition 3.2. The universal covering of a based object $(A,\alpha)$ is defined by comprehensive factorisation $\star_{\mathcal{E}}\to\mathcal{U}_{\alpha}\to A$ of $\alpha$. The fundamental group $\pi_{1}(A,\alpha)$ is the group of automorphisms of $u_{\alpha}:\mathcal{U}_{\alpha}\to A$ fixing $A$.
Definition 1.15. An adjunction $i:\mathcal{D}\rightleftarrows\mathcal{E}:r$ is called $P$-reflecting for a comprehension scheme $P$ on $\mathcal{D}$ if the left adjoint $r:\mathcal{E}\to\mathcal{D}$ induces slice functors $\mathcal{E}/B\to\mathcal{D}/r(B)$ with fully faithful right adjoint restrictions $\mathrm{Cov}_{r(B)}\to\mathcal{E}/B$. If $i:\mathcal{D}\hookrightarrow\mathcal{E}$ is a full embedding, $\mathcal{D}$ is called a $P$-reflective subcategory of $\,\mathcal{E}$.
Definition 4.1. (1) For a $T\in\mathcal{T}$ and $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathop{\mathbf{Spc}}\nolimits\mathcal{T}^{c}$, let $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathop{\mathbf{supp}}\nolimits T$ if for all Thomason subsets $\mathbf{V},\mathbf{U}\subseteq\mathop{\mathbf{Spc}}\nolimits\mathcal{T}^{c}$, with $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathbf{V}\cap{\mathbf{U}}^{\mathbf{c}}$ $\Gamma_{\mathbf{V}}L_{\mathbf{U}}T\neq 0.$ (2) The localising space $\mathop{\mathbf{Lspc}}\nolimits\mathcal{T}$ will be the set $\mathop{\mathbf{Spc}}\nolimits\mathcal{T}^{c}$ with the topology generated by $\mathbf{V}\cap{\mathbf{U}}^{\mathbf{c}}$ with $\mathbf{V},\mathbf{U}\subseteq\mathop{\mathbf{Spc}}\nolimits\mathcal{T}^{c}$ Thomason. In short $\mathop{\mathbf{Lspc}}\nolimits\mathcal{T}={\rm\bf skula}\!\left(\mathop{% \mathbf{HSpc}}\nolimits\mathcal{T}^{c}\right).$ We will refer to this topology as the localising topology.
