Definition 6.1. (1) For any element $T\in\mathcal{T}$, set $\mathcal{A}\!\left(T\right)=\{S\in\mathcal{T}\mid T\otimes S=0\}.$ Any class of the form $\mathcal{A}\!\left(T\right)$ is called Bousfield. (2) A Bousfield class $\mathcal{A}\!\left(T\right)$ is idempotent if $\mathcal{A}\!\left(T\right)=\mathcal{A}\!\left(T\otimes T\right)$. (3) Let $\mathbb{D}\!\left(\mathcal{T}\right)$ denote the collection of idempotent Bousfield classes. Order $\mathbb{D}\!\left(\mathcal{T}\right)$ via reverse inclusion. The elements $\mathcal{A}\!\left(1\right)$ and $\mathcal{A}\!\left(0\right)$ are the maximum and minimum respectively.
