Definition 7.10. Let $R$ be a commutative ring and $I\subseteq R$ and ideal. A prime $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathop{\mathbf{Spec}}\nolimits R$ is an essential divisor of $I$ if $\mathfrak{p}$ is an essential prime of $\sqrt{I}$ in the frame of radical ideals. This means that $\mathfrak{p}\in\min I$ but $\sqrt{I}\neq\bigcap_{\begin{subarray}{c}\mathfrak{p}\in\min(I)\\ \mathfrak{p}\neq\mathfrak{q}\end{subarray}}\mathfrak{q}$
Definition 2.9. Let $\mathbb{X}$ be a frame. (1) An element $\mathbbm{p}\in\mathbb{X}$ is meet irreducible or prime if for any $\mathbbm{x},\mathbbm{y}\in\mathbb{X}$ $\mathbbm{x}\land\mathbbm{y}\leq\mathbbm{p}$ implies either $\mathbbm{x}\leq\mathbbm{p}$ or $\mathbbm{y}\leq\mathbbm{p}$. (2) Let $\mathop{\mathbf{Spc}}\nolimits\mathbb{X}$ be the set of meet irreducible elements of $\mathbb{X}$. (3) For any $\mathbbm{x}\in\mathbb{X}$, let $\mathbf{D}(\mathbbm{x})\subseteq\mathop{\mathbf{Spc}}\nolimits\mathbb{X}$ be the meet irreducible $\mathbbm{p}$ such that $\mathbbm{x}\nleq\mathbbm{p}$.
Definition 2.1. A space $\mathbf{X}$ is called spectral if (a) $\mathbf{X}$ is $\mathop{\rm T}\nolimits_{0}$ (b) every irreducible closed set $\mathbf{V}\subseteq\mathbf{X}$ has a generic point, i.e. there is a $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathbf{V}$ such that $\mathbf{V}=\bar{\mathfrak{p}}$ (c) the quasi-compact open subsets of $\mathbf{X}$ are a basis (d) the intersection of any two quasi-compact open sets is again quasi-compact open (e) the space $\mathbf{X}$ is quasi-compact.
Definition 1.1. For an arbitrary commutative ring $R$ and a complex $M$ of $R$-modules, we say $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathop{\mathbf{Spec}}\nolimits R$ is in $\mathop{\mathbf{supp}}\nolimits M$ if for every finite subset ${\underline{x}=x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\in\mathfrak{p}}$, the cohomology ${\rm H}^{i}{\rm K}_{\infty}\!\left(\underline{x}\colon\!M_{\mathfrak{p}}\right% )={\rm H}^{i}\!\big{(}(R\to R_{x_{1}})\otimes\cdots\otimes(R\to R_{x_{n}})% \otimes M_{\mathfrak{p}}\big{)}\neq 0$ does not vanish for some $i\in\mathbb{Z}$.
Definition 7.1. (1) An element $\mathbbm{x}$ of a frame $\mathbb{X}$ is complemented if there exists an element ${\mathbbm{x}}^{{\rm c}}\in\mathbb{X}$ such that $\mathbbm{x}\land{\mathbbm{x}}^{{\rm c}}=0$ and $\mathbbm{x}\lor{\mathbbm{x}}^{{\rm c}}=1$. We call ${\mathbbm{x}}^{{\rm c}}$ the complement of $\mathbbm{x}$. (2) A frame homomorphism $\alpha\colon\mathbb{X}\to\mathbb{Y}$ is complemented if $\alpha(\mathbbm{x})$ is complemented in $\mathbb{Y}$ for every $\mathbbm{x}\in\mathbb{X}$. (3) A nucleus of a frame $\mathbb{X}$ is a function $\nu\colon\mathbb{X}\to\mathbb{X}$ satisfying the following. (a) $\mathbbm{x}\leq\nu(\mathbbm{x})$ for all $\mathbbm{x}\in\mathbb{X}$ (b) $\mathbbm{x}\leq\mathbbm{y}$ implies $\nu(\mathbbm{x})\leq\nu(\mathbbm{y})$ for all $\mathbbm{x},\mathbbm{y}\in\mathbb{X}$ (c) $\nu\nu(\mathbbm{x})=\nu(\mathbbm{x})$ for all $\mathbbm{x}\in\mathbb{X}$ (d) $\nu(\mathbbm{x}\land\mathbbm{y})=\nu(\mathbbm{x})\land\nu(\mathbbm{y})$ for all $\mathbbm{x},\mathbbm{y}\in\mathbb{X}$ (4) For a frame $\mathbb{X}$, let $\mathbb{N}\!\left(\mathbb{X}\right)$ denote the set of Nuclei. We call $\mathbb{N}\!\left(\mathbb{X}\right)$ the assembly of $\mathbb{X}$. The assembly is partially ordered in the following manner: for nuclei $\nu,\mu\in\mathbb{N}\!\left(\mathbb{X}\right)$, we say that $\nu\leq\mu$ if $\nu(\mathbbm{x})\leq\mu(\mathbbm{x})$ for all $\mathbbm{x}\in\mathbb{X}$. (5) For every element of a frame $\mathbbm{x}\in\mathbb{X}$, let $\nu_{\mathbbm{x}}\colon\mathbb{X}\to\mathbb{X}$ be the nucleus defined by $\mathbbm{y}\mapsto\mathbbm{y}\land\mathbbm{x}$.
Definition 3.5. (1) A subcategory $\mathcal{L}\subseteq\mathcal{T}$ is localising if it is thick and closed under arbitrary set-indexed coproducts. A localising subcategory $\mathcal{L}$ is a tensor ideal if for every $T\in\mathcal{L}$ and $S\in\mathcal{T}$, $S\otimes T$ is in $\mathcal{L}$ (2) For any Thomason subset $\mathbf{V}\subseteq\mathop{\mathbf{Spc}}\nolimits\mathcal{T}^{c}$, let $\mathcal{T}_{\mathbf{V}}$ be the generated by the compact object $C\in\mathcal{T}^{c}$ such that $\mathop{\mathbf{Supp}}\nolimits C\subseteq\mathbf{V}.$ We call $\mathcal{T}_{\mathbf{V}}$ the $\mathbf{V}$-acyclic objects of $\mathcal{T}$. (3) An object $T\in\mathcal{T}$ is $\mathbf{V}$-local if ${\rm Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}\left(\mathcal{T}_{\mathbf{V}},T\right)=0$ or equivalently ${\rm Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}\left({\mathcal{T}_{\mathbf{V}}}^{c},T\right)=0.$
Definition 7.14. A space is scattered if every closed subset has an isolated point which is a point which is open in the subspace topology. A space is Hochster scattered if it is spectral and the Hochster dual is scattered.
Definition 1.3. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a rigidly compactly generated tensor triangulated category. For a prime in the Balmer spectrum $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathop{\mathbf{Spc}}\nolimits\mathcal{T}^{c}$ and an object $T\in\mathcal{T}$, we say $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathop{\mathbf{supp}}\nolimits T$ if for every Thomason subset $\mathbf{V}\subseteq\mathop{\mathbf{Spc}}\nolimits\mathcal{T}$ with $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathbf{V}$, $\Gamma_{\mathbf{V}}T_{\mathfrak{p}}\neq 0.$ We call $\mathcal{T}$ supportive if support detects vanishing, i.e. $\mathop{\mathbf{supp}}\nolimits T=\emptyset$ if and only if $T=0$.
Definition 2.3. Let $\mathbf{X}$ be a spectral space. (1) A subset $\mathbf{V}\subseteq\mathbf{X}$ is Thomason if it is the union of complements of quasi-compact open sets. (2) The quasi-compact open sets of a spectral space form a closed base, and the topology that they define is called the Hochster dual of $\mathbf{X}$ and denoted $\mathbf{X}^{\dagger}$. The open subsets of $\mathbf{X}^{\dagger}$ are the Thomason subsets of $\mathbf{X}$.
Definition 2.7. (1) A complete lattice is a partially ordered set $\mathbb{L}$ such that every subset admits both a supremum and an infimum, i.e. a join denoted $\lor$ and a meet denoted $\land$. In particular every frame has a maximum and minimum denoted by $1_{\mathbb{L}}$ and $0_{\mathbb{L}}$ respectively, or more often simply 1 and 0. (2) A frame $\mathbb{X}$ is a complete lattice such that for every $\mathbbm{x}\in\mathbb{X}$ and $\{\mathbbm{y}_{i}\}\subseteq\mathbb{F}$ satisfies $\mathbbm{x}\land\bigvee_{i}\mathbbm{y}_{i}=\bigvee_{i}\mathbbm{x}\land\mathbbm% {y}_{i}.$ (3) A map $\varphi\colon\mathbb{X}\to\mathbb{Y}$ between frames is a frame homomorphism if (a) $\varphi$ preserves the maximum and minimum, i.e. $\varphi(1_{\mathbb{X}})=1_{\mathbb{Y}}\quad\quad\quad\quad\varphi(0_{\mathbb{X% }})=0_{\mathbb{Y}}$ (b) $\varphi$ preserves arbitrary joins, i.e. every $\{\mathbbm{x}_{i}\}\subseteq\mathbb{X}$ satisfies $\varphi\left(\bigvee_{i}\mathbbm{x}_{i}\right)=\bigvee_{i}\varphi(\mathbbm{x}_% {i})$ (c) $\varphi$ preserves finite meets, i.e. every $\mathbbm{x},\mathbbm{y}\in\mathbb{X}$ satisfies $\varphi(\mathbbm{x}\land\mathbbm{y})=\varphi(\mathbbm{x})\land\varphi(\mathbbm% {y}).$ (4) Let $\mathop{\rm\textit{{Frm}}}\nolimits$ be the category of frames and frame homomorphisms.
Definition 7.8. A spectral space $\mathbf{X}$ is Hochster weakly scattered if its Hochster dual $\mathbf{X}^{\dagger}$ is weakly scattered. By Example 2.5, $\mathbf{X}$ is Hochster weakly scattered if and only if for every Thomason subset $\mathbf{U}\subseteq\mathbf{X}$, there exists a point $\mathfrak{p}\notin\mathbf{U}$ and a Thomason subset $\mathbf{V}\subseteq\mathbf{X}$ such that $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathbf{V}\cap{\mathbf{U}}^{\mathbf{c}}\subseteq\downarrow% \mathfrak{p}.$
